dbl:section.dbl:para:
To be able to parse an &xml; file, you have to provide an element class
for every element type that appears in the file. Defining an element class
for an element named cool works like this:


class cool(xsc.Element):
	empty = 0

	def convert(self, converter):
		node = html.b(self.content, " is cool!")
		return node.convert(converter)


You have to derive your new class from xsc.Element.
The name of the class will be the element name. For element type names that are no valid Python
identifiers, you can use the class attribute name in the element class the overwrite
the element name.

All attribute values are instances of subclasses of the class Attr. Available subclasses are:
TextAttr, for normal text attributes;
URLAttr, for attributes that are URLs;
BoolAttr, for boolean attributes (such an attribute is either present or not, but it's value will be ignored);
IntAttr, for integer attributes;
ColorAttr, for color attributes (e.g. #ffffff)
Attr itself is derived from Frag so it is possible to use all the sequence methods on an attribute. Unset attributes will be treated like empty ones so the following is possible:
del node["spam"] node["spam"].append("ham")
this also means that after
del node["spam"][0]
the attribute will be empty again and will be considered to be unset. Such attributes will be ignored when publishing.

Defining processing instructions works the same way. Derive a
new class from xist.xsc.ProcInst
and implement convert.
The following example implements a processing instruction that returns an uppercase
version of it's content as a text node.


class upper(xsc.ProcInst):
	def convert(self, converter):
		return xsc.Text(self.content.upper())


it can be used in an &xml; file as following:

<?upper foo?>

All these methods use the method publish internally. publish gets passed an instance of xist.publisher.Publisher (or one of it's subclasses). All strings generated will be send to the publish method of the publisher. write uses FilePublisher and asBytes uses BytePublisher. For example FilePublisher looks like this:
class FilePublisher(Publisher): def __init__(self, file, base=None, encoding=None, XHTML=None, publishPrefix=0): Publisher.__init__(self, base=base, encoding=encoding, XHTML=XHTML, publishPrefix=publishPrefix) (encode, decode, streamReaderClass, streamWriterClass) = codecs.lookup(self.encoding) self.file = streamWriterClass(file)
def publish(self, text): self.file.write(text)
